<font color="#FF0000">A FEW GOOD MEN REFUSE TO SING </font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov 16 15:03:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
And a few good men refuse to sing soprano<br><br>
Washington Times, Published in Washington, D.C<br>
5am -- November 14, 1997 <br>
Wesley Pruden is editor in chief of The Times<br><br>
Sara Lister is sadder if not much wiser this morning. She learned the hard way that sometimes you can't tell it to the Marines. <br>
The assistant secretary of the Army, who has blisters on her bottom the size of Susan B. Anthony dollars, is sadder not because her characterization of the Marines as &quot;extremists&quot; who wear &quot;checkerboard uniforms and stuff&quot; might have hurt the feelings of heroes, but because she got caught at insulting them. <br>
. . . . When she called the Marines &quot;extremists&quot; and belittled the uniform that has returned from all the nation's wars soaked in the blood of men who gave arms, legs and often their lives for their country, she imagined that she was talking to academics and nerds who agreed with her.<br>
. . . . This is clear from the &quot;apology&quot; that, under extraordinary pressure, she sent Thursday to Gen. Charles Krulak, the commandant of the Marine Corps. &quot;I regret that the use of this term during an academic discussion has generated a controversy that does not represent my views or those of the Army. ... My remarks were not intended to denigrate the Marine Corps in any way. It is unfortunate that they were misinterpreted.&quot;<br>
. . . . Naturally, she used the hoariest of all the excuses politicians and other scoundrels and scoundrelettes use when they have to answer to accurate transcripts of their stupidities: Her remarks were &quot;taken out of context&quot; and &quot;misinterpreted.&quot;<br>
. . . . But Mrs. Lister, whose mouth could use something a little stronger than Listerine, is not the chief villain in this sordid episode. She should get a little credit for forthrightness, since she was expressing the contempt, derision and revulsion for the military and all its works that is the single most consistent theme of Bill Clinton and his administration. The flower children who preside in the White House have learned nothing and forgotten nothing since they set out to destroy the culture and despoil their inheritance three decades ago. She is in her job because that's who Bill and Hillary want in her job, someone to preside over the feminization and dismantling of the nation's military so that America will never again be a threat to the world &quot;village.&quot;<br>
. . . . Bill and Hillary and the flower children are deaf to the music of America and blind to the grandeur of their native land, and just as it's not fair to blame a buzzard for dining on the wreck on the highway, maybe it's not fair to blame them for giving white-trash behavior a bad name. The White House declined Thursday to scold Mrs. Lister or say anything nice about the Marines. When Mike McCurry, the president's press agent, was asked what he made of Sara Lister's insults, he pretended not to be aware of the incident. Like his boss when caught in scandal and lawlessness, he pleads incompetence. How could a press agent not be aware of the front-page story everyone's talking about?<br>
. . . . Men who know better act as if they don't. A secretary of defense of a more responsible era, Democrat or Republican, would have expected to find Mrs. Lister's resignation on his desk Thursday morning. Bill Cohen sent his own press agent out with the mealy-mouth wish that her apology, such as it is, &quot;puts the issue to rest.&quot; If Janet Reno gets to keep her job after the feds fry the children at Waco, doesn't anything go?<br>
. . . . Two senators -- Conrad Burns of Montana and Paul Coverdell of Georgia -- demand that Mrs. Lister summon the decency to quit now, and if, as certain Pentagon figures insist, President Clinton intends to try to appoint Mrs. Lister to succeed Togo West as secretary of the Army, she may get a public spanking. It's difficult to imagine how even this Republican majority in the Senate would confirm her. President Clinton trying is easier to imagine.<br>
. . . . Mrs. Lister's insults stirred bipartisan anger. Sen. Chuck Robb of Virginia, who commanded a Marine rifle company in Vietnam, says the incident stirs his angry juices, and even Sen. John Glenn of Ohio, who pretended to see no evil and hear no evidence of Clinton chicanery in the Senate campaign-finance hearings (gritting his teeth to do it for the queen), pays tribute to the Corps as men who are always ready to answer the president's &quot;call to 911&quot; when national disaster looms. He can't quite bring himself to demand that Sara Lister be cashiered, but nobody's prefect.<br>
. . . . What really bothers Mrs. Lister about the Marines is that they have refused to stand still while she and the feminist fellow travelers at the Pentagon make sopranos of them. Gen. Krulak and his men understand what war is about, and what it takes to fight one. Much of the senior leadership of the Army, sad to say, has gone over the hill, to wait to pick up the pieces when the real world teaches us all a lesson we won't soon forget. Sara and her sisters can appreciate male timidity, even nurture it. But never the insolence of men who intend to remain men, whatever it costs.<br><br>
. . . .. <br>
 <br><br>

